<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="113" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="113">
<taxonomicName authorityName="K. W. Xu &amp; G. L. Xu" authorityYear="2022" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Aspleniaceae" genus="Asplenium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Asplenium jiulianshanense" order="Polypodiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="113" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="jiulianshanense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Asplenium jiulianshanense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
somewhat resembles 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. kiangsuense" pageId="0" pageNumber="113" rank="species" species="kiangsuense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">A. kiangsuense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its small size, rachises adaxially without a deep furrow, pinnae elliptic to trapeziform-oblong, sori 3-4 per pinna in the middle part of frond. However, the former has rachises with only one gemma near apex, pinnae (15-)20-35 pairs, pinna margins entire to sparsely crenate, exospore length 37-43 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, while the latter has rachises without gemmae near the apex, pinnae 8-20(-22) pairs, pinna margins entire to sinuate, exospore length 31-36 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
